{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 20:47:19.146793", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos fabric (super-spine / spine / leaf) with EBGP, pods hosting DNS + web servers\\n\\nSummary\\n- Current assessment: network is healthy. No loss of reachability or service-level failures observed for the examined hosts and services.\\n- Key evidence: DNS resolution works from client_0, ICMP probes to servers show 0% packet loss and low RTTs, webserver process is listening on port 80, and FRR routing/BGP tables show the expected pod prefixes propagated across the fabric.\\n\\nActions / tests performed\\n- Collected global reachability matrix (ping-based) between clients, DNS servers, and web servers.\\n- Checked network configuration on: client_0, dns_pod0, webserver0_pod0 (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route).\\n- Queried DNS from client_0 (dig/host against pod DNS).\\n- Ping from client_0 to dns_pod0.\\n- Checked listening services on webserver0_pod0 (netstat -tuln).\\n- Retrieved BGP configuration / routing tables from FRR routers: leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0.\\n\\nResults / findings (detailed)\\n\\n1) Reachability (L3/L2)\\n- The reachability summary shows successful pings across the fabric for the sampled hosts. Most measured pairs report:\\n  - 0% packet loss,\\n  - sub-5 ms RTTs (typical for this simulated topology).\\n- A couple of ping entries in the reachability report were marked \"unknown\" for source webserver0_pod0 to other destinations — this appears to be an artifact of the reachability sampling (not an observed packet loss or drop). All other probes that included those endpoints (from other sources) succeeded.\\n\\n2) Host network configurations\\n- client_0:\\n  - IP: 192.168.0.2/24, default via 192.168.0.1.\\n  - /etc/resolv.conf contains pod DNS servers: 10.0.0.2, 10.1.0.2, 10.2.0.2, 10.3.0.2.\\n- dns_pod0:\\n  - IP: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1.\\n  -icmp from client_0 reached it with ~2.8 ms average RTT and 0% loss.\\n- webserver0_pod0:\\n  - IP: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1.\\n  - netstat shows a process listening on 0.0.0.0:80 (python http.server present).\\n\\n3) DNS\\n- From client_0: dig @10.0.0.2 web0.pod0 returned 10.0.1.2 (correct authoritative mapping for pod0/web0).\\n- DNS servers are reachable from client_0 and from other DNS servers (as evidenced by reachability matrix).\\n\\n4) HTTP service (application-level)\\n- webserver0_pod0 is listening on port 80 (netstat confirmed).\\n- The reachability tests from clients and other servers to ranges that include 10.0.1.2 are successful (ICMP); combined with DNS resolution and listening socket, service-level access appears possible. No HTTP fetch was explicitly run, but no network-level impediment was observed.\\n\\n5) Routing / BGP (control plane)\\n- FRR BGP tables and routing shows:\\n  - Pod service subnets (10.<pod>.<idx>.0/24) are present and advertised across routers.\\n  - Each leaf that should own a pod subnet appears to have the connected route available; other routers show that subnet via EBGP nexthops (multiple paths visible).\\n  - Several prefixes (including a /25 for 10.0.1.0/25) appear in the BGP tables where expected and the FIB selection is consistent with the topology (connected on the correct leaf/router in the route outputs).\\n  - Multi-paths/multiple nexthops are present as expected in a Clos fabric with multiple adjacencies; selected routes are in place (no missing prefixes).\\n- No BGP session flaps, withdrawn prefixes, or obviously malformed AS-paths were observed in the sampled outputs.\\n\\nAnomalies / irregularities observed\\n- No functional anomalies detected: all probed dataplane flows succeed with 0% packet loss; DNS resolution works; webserver listens on port 80.\\n- Minor observations that are not evidence of failure but worth noting:\\n  - A small portion of the reachability output shows \"unknown\" status for pings sourced from webserver0_pod0. This is likely a sampling/measurement omission (the same host was reachable when probed from other sources).\\n  - Several retrieved router outputs were truncated (tool output length limits). The truncated sections prevented a full line-by-line audit of every BGP attribute/neighbor state, but the visible portions are consistent and show expected advertisement of pod prefixes.\\n\\nLocalization (faulty devices / areas)\\n- No devices showed signs of failure. The data collected indicates:\\n  - client_0 can reach DNS servers and pods.\\n  - dns_pod0 is reachable and authoritative for pod0 (client query returned expected A record).\\n  - webserver0_pod0 has local network config and HTTP service listening.\\n  - Leaf, spine, and super-spine routers have the expected BGP routes in their RIBs/FIBs.\\n- Therefore: no specific device or link can be identified as faulty based on the collected evidence.\\n\\nRoot-cause analysis\\n- Since no service failures, packet loss, route absence, or misconfiguration symptoms were observed in the collected data, there is no root cause to identify for a failure.\\n- The observed behavior is consistent with a correctly functioning Clos fabric and BGP-based route propagation.\\n\\nCaveats / limitations\\n- Some router outputs were large and truncated by the tool; full BGP neighbor/session status details and full config lines were not completely available in the captured result set. The visible parts, however, show consistent route propagation.\\n- No explicit end-to-end HTTP GET test was executed from client_0 to http://web0.pod0 (only DNS resolution, ICMP, and local server listening checks). Given DNS and ICMP success and server listening on port 80, application connectivity is strongly indicated but not fully proven by an HTTP transaction in these logs.\\n- The reachability check used a sampling method (not every possible pair was probed); unprobed pairs could theoretically hide isolated issues — but the sampled set includes representative client → DNS and client → webserver flows.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network shows normal operation: routing is converged, DNS resolution is correct, hosts are reachable with no packet loss, and the HTTP server is running and listening.\\n- No anomalies or root causes of failures were found in the collected evidence.\\n\\nIf you want further, targeted evidence-gathering (traceroutes for specific flows, full BGP neighbor show outputs, full FRR configs, or an actual HTTP GET from client_0 to web0.pod0), I can run those next — but per your request I have not included mitigation steps., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='bcbd5967-cb1f-4e23-ac97-4988ef5bbdf0'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
